author: @MaximGhost
comments: A warning about Amazon's revenue growth that you see ... The high profit margin revenue growth used to be from Amazon's AWS cloud business-to-business services.  However, the growth of Microsoft's Azure has been cutting into AWS's growth.  I work in IT for a large financial company who uses cloud infrastructure ... more often than not, companies in our industry use Azure instead of AWS since Microsoft offers better prices.  So the Amazon's growth that you see is likely from the retail side, which is much more competitive and thus less profitable.  For that reason, I hold more MSFT shares than I do AMZN shares.

comments: I'm not sure how it looks from the outside, but those of us who work for Amazon think that some of the moves related to Whole Foods and Amazon Fresh makes it look like that Amazon is looking to sell Whole Foods in the near future. Some things they have done recently is implementing a delivery fee for Whole Foods customers while eliminating the fee for Amazon Fresh customers. Amazon is also currently in the process of removing all Amazon shoppers from Whole Foods and converting these workers into Amazon Fresh shoppers or warehouse pickers which is leaving Whole Foods barren with very few people actually able to shop. So, the online customers are not getting their groceries shopped. Whole Foods is hemorrhaging money from Amazon so getting it of their books makes sense, especially with Amazon Fresh being what it is.

author: @jacobamason
comments:
This misses the mark a bit. As other commenters have pointed out, warehouse employees aren't currently getting paid with stock. Salaried tech employees make mid six figures and get several shares a years. To most amazon employees who currently get compensation via shares, the split is mostly meaningless. I would wager that the reason for the afterhours activity is solely based on the share buybacks, which, as you mentioned, is very rare. I think investors think that Amazon is reducing share dilution through buy backs and will continue to do so in the future. Stock splits don't make it easier to buy or sell in the current year. Most trading activity from institutional investors do not care. Most Robinhood users who buy and sell fractional do not care. Most retail investors who buy and sell mutual funds or indices do not care.
Disclaimer: I am a high-salaried tech employee who gets a significant portion of my salary in amzn stock. I don't have any insight into the internal decision-making process around the split. This is my own opinion as someone whose net worth consists of a whole lot of amzn.

author: @xvx4848
comments: I'm so happy I sold my portfolio as a new year's resolution. This upcoming 90% crash is going to blindside most investors, especially the newer ones. I'd rather have as much cash as possible going into this crash. People aren't coming to grips with how overvalued the market is quite yet and the "buy the dip" mentality is allowing institutional investors to unload their upcoming losses onto newer freshman investors that don't understand the system. Every time the market "dips" its those institutional investors are offloading some of their shares, but not so many that they lose significant sums of money. Then they wait for people to "buy the dip" to drive the price back up. Rinse and repeat. This is why no matter how green the day is, the market just keeps falling. Eventually it'll fall off a cliff and crash and I feel terrible for people who don't realize this quite yet.

author: @JosephCarlsonAfterHours
comments:
Maybe I worded this wrong - but the point is that even if a company has solid fundamentals being less investable may still keep money out of the stock. 

In the case of Amazon I think it makes sense for the stock to move up after a stock split because it makes the company more investable. Whether we like to admit it or not, having more investors access to a stock in any way helps support the stock price. 

Why do investors celebrate SPY inclusion of their stock? Because it helps support the stock price. 

Why do investors celebrate DOW inclusion of their stock? Because it helps support the stock price.

Why do investors celebrate stock splits? Because it helps support the stock price. 

Just as the example in the video. If Cheerios started to only sell their cereal in bulk orders of 20 boxes, even though the value (fundamentals) would be identical. The fact that you can only buy it in massive bulk would certainly reduce the overall sales. Allowing people the ability to buy or sell something with less friction of course affects the amount of volume of that thing.

author: @lolitajones859
comments: It does matter how many shares you have.  There's a multiplier.  Look at it this way: Regardless of what the price of a stock, if you have 1 share of that stock - that literally means for every dollar that stock goes up, you are 1 dollar richer.... however, if you have 20 shares of a stock, for every dollar it goes up you are now $20 dollars richer.  Makes a big difference.  If you have 1 share of Amazon and it goes up $100, you are $100 dollars richer.  If you have 20 shares of Amazon and it goes up $100, you are $2,000. richer. BIG BIG BIG Diference.

author: @markvanderlugt5041
comments:
David- it‚Äôs really all about risk management- how much are you willing to invest/ able to budget for investing. At this time in the market, it‚Äôs a little rocky, so you‚Äôre getting in at a decently discounted market. However, there‚Äôs still a little bit of over value in it. Be careful and do as much research as you possibly can. ETF‚Äôs are very good risk management vehicles for your money. Since you‚Äôre new to investing, you should research a number of ETF‚Äôs for your budget. 

My keys for you:
Watch the news- politics are a huge factor. Research economics. Research stocks. Research ETF‚Äôs. Stocks are like sports- you have a game, where a ball is being played with and you have to try and figure out where the ball will be next, so you can get it and score. Inflation means higher prices= look at stocks with pricing power. Rising interest rates are also a common theme- tech stocks get hurt the most from them, but finance stocks do well. 

I hope this helps!
Goodluck!!!

author: @rcg5317
comments: About excess capacity: Amazon is a key player in supply chain management. One of the weaknesses of current supply chain theory is Just In Time and reliance on a cheap and high capacity supply chain. Pandemic and fuel prices has shown that model has vulnerability. So the idea of some warehousing of supplies and finished goods is being reconsidered. This is not only a good idea for Amazon for its own use but it can lease that capacity to others as a service same as they do in AWS for data storage.

author: @financialnews9151
comments:
Three important points in my opinion:
1. They overbuilt during a time building costs were at record highs. Double ouch and terrible for cash flow.
2. If you think filling your tank is bad right now, think about how much Amazon is spending on fuel. Ouch! I think we are currently seeing the negative aspects of offering free shipping and free returns. 
3. I think out of all the "big tech" companies, Amazon deserves the lowest valuation multiple which is not the case right now. Most of their business, except for AWS, is low margin and very capital intensive. I have a feeling AWS will be spun off one day to unlock shareholder value.

author: @delongzhai4887
comments:
I think this is a great video. However there are factors that I don't think Amazon can be considered as a buy even at this price.

1. Amazon not doing a spin under Andy Jassy, nor if he ever interested in that. I consider this to be risk #1, conglomerates with multiple businesses operated in different industry do fall apart significantly if the management is not qualified to make decisions considering the complexities of their businesses. examples: Johnson & Johnson(consumer products and pharmaceutical), GE(aviation, healthcare, and energy), AT&T. These are the companies that recently did some form of restructuring but there will be more coming.

2. Amazon invest every penny they earned. This both have upside and downside. The upside is Amazon reinvest back to itself, so it can continue to grow. The downside is it return no profit to shareholders. How am I assured that 10 years from now, Amazon will grow nonstop and remain unbeatable. Amazon and its management have huge ambitions but they also need to pay attention to capital allocation.

3. True value in Amazon is difficult to calculate. If we break Amazon down to B2B(AWS), B2C(eCommerce, Prime, Kindle, Ads), how much does AWS worth, and how much does eCommerce worth? Can eCommerce survive without the cash flow from AWS? Can Amazon face less scrutiny if Amazon is breakup into two (with less market multiple on Amazon.com given low profit margin)? Can B2C be split further into eCommerce with ads, and prime that provide better experience for any consumers(not just Amazon) whenever they use free shipping, music, video, kindle (those bundled features) and eventually become a subscription powerhouse.

4. Union, government anti-trust law (both EU, US) both poses managerial risk to Amazon. Union is troublesome given the massive labor force that Amazon logistic have. and Anti-trust, how can it sounds logically and politically correct if Amazon is both competing with its 3rd party merchant and selling its own merchandise. Will the advertisement create a bad reputation that the poor-quality products been displayed first to the users.

when a company does not pay out dividend, you would only expected to profit if someone else will buy your stock. as an investor, you will have less options to make money. Hence investors need a higher margin of safety, but since Amazon is difficult to assess, it become hard to even begin with. That's okay if you are young, but for me, as I enter into my 30s, my 40, my 50. I would expect to have greater dividend payout. Does this change in investment style require me to sell Amazon and pay long term capital taxes to the government?

author: @helshabini
comments:
FYI, the AWS commitments are usually spent over multiple years, not a single year. So you can expect those $89b to become revenue over the next 3-5 years. The reason they do it is that big companies can get AWS service at a discount if they commit to using it for the long term. So big companies project their cloud spend over time, and make those large commitments. The nature of these commitments are also usually backloaded, since for any given company they expect their cloud spend in the first year of the contract to be significantly less than the last year, as they grow and migrate more and more stuff to the cloud over the length of the commitment. 
This is not to discount the fact that $89b of commitments is huge. But just to take into perspective a more accurate representation of how and when those dollars are going to hit Amazon's financial statement.

comments:
37:00 I have worked also with AWS, Azure and GCP (Google Cloud Platform) and I think that is not that much difference in services, AWS can't compete with Google or Microsoft AI nor data services like S3 (S3 = Azure Blob Storage = GCP Cloud Storage, same service so that 1.5T valuation for S3 is a complete exaggeration) which is not a "data lake" service as the Barron's writer says, the only cloud that offers a data lake as one full service is Azure, AWS and GCP is a set of multiple services. I mean, it is not bad, but it is just ok... let's hope this still continue enough to stick with all that market share. Even that startups "picks AWS" (I've seen more startups picking GCP than AWS in my case), big corporations tends to use Microsoft Azure because their easier integration with all Microsoft ecosystem. 

I would be happier that Amazon get stronger in their main business (ecommerce) and optimize processes to wide margins, Amazon is a merciless beast on that sector, but cloud is a really bloody fight.

author: @Fail.Better
comments:
I find it very interesting(not negative) that you,  a software guy, who understands technology and its impacts better than most, who loves companies like Apple for their moat and margin, would double down on Amazon before Microsoft. Nobody would argue that AWS is a beast with tons of profit and value, but Azure is right on their heels, and with a few key contracts(like Netflix moving over from AWS for example), we could start to see an acceleration that leads to AWS and Azure at full parity. After that, when you compare the remaining businesses of both companies, I would say Microsoft wins hands down, no questions asked. Amazon competes in a million different businesses and wins many of them, but at high cost, with it eating most(if not all) of their Margin. Microsoft doesn't have this issue. Microsoft is almost like combining the best parts of Netflix, Adobe, AWS and Salesforce into a single company that pays dividends, and with a larger moat than any would have individually.

I know you're a "fan" of Microsoft, but honestly, you're really not. You haven't invested nearly as heavily into it as you have in Apple or Amazon(or really even Netflix). I don't get it, man. author: @angelcovarrubias3418
comments: AMZN at the end of the day has single digit return on assets and single digit return on invested capital. And that is what an investor in AMZN will earn over the long haul - the Return on Assets/Capital. WMT and COST will keep the bulk of AMZN revenues at single digit profitability margins (FCF as a percentage of revenue and profit margin) as well. The future for AMZN  investors will look much like that of WMT investors because by and large the fundamentals (Returns/Margins for the bulk of revenues) and growth story are playing out closely - market perform.

author: @HermannTheGreat
comments: Cstco and Wmt/SamsClub are constantly flooded during the week, especially on weekends. They have little competition from amzn for repeated purchases at this point.

author: @angelcovarrubias3418
comments:
@@carsonweekley1539 AMZN simply can NOT raise prices/margins the way AMZN bulls claim it could on the bulk of revenues or even on the fastest portion of revenues. WMT and COST and TGT are pretty "built out" and can they simply "raise prices/margins whenever they want"? No and neither can AMZN. MSFT and GOOG provide pricing pressure on AWS in a similar manner and  every other business AMZN is in to a significant extent is the same way outside of 3P.

The idea that AMZN can simply "spin up margins" will be the last sacred cow to be slaughtered by the reality of competition from MSFT/GOOGL in cloud and META/GOOGL in Ads and WMT, COST, TGT and the rest of the retailers in 1P. 

3P granted they have pricing power and it remains to be seen how much they could squeeze 3P before they get to much grumbling and more defections to SHOP, WMT, ETSY or whatever options are there (not many and not good - 3P is pretty captive right now and Prime makes 3P want to stay).

author: @JosephCarlsonAfterHours
comments: To be clear. Raising prices is not and has never been part of my investment thesis in Amazon. In my 40 minute video I also never mentioned raising prices as part of the bull case. There‚Äôs significant cost structure and working capital improvements Amazon can do, raising margin, without raising prices to end consumer. The only place that I actually see Amazon have pricing power and raising prices is prime membership.

author: @angelcovarrubias3418
comments:
@@carsonweekley1539 On cost reductions that seems an even heavier lift as the fulfillment is extremely labor intensive and last mile requires constant  upkeep even of EV delivery vans (even if owned by subcontractors). To "roboticize" the centers will take even more capex. Discount retail is what it is - low margin. 

It's difficult to make an argument for AMZN at substantially more than market weight but I appreciate the bull thesis.

It's not much different than the bull thesis for WMT: The costs will be brought down substantially and that will increase margins. 

The big returns for discount retail (WMT then and AMZN now) are when the companies were growing fast, new stores for WMT and new FC for AMZN - once growth slows discount retail is low margin and not much room on cost control when you are already WMT and AMZN.

Here is where COST looks superb in comparison to both WMT and AMZN and I think the COST management has been hall of fame/GOAT in discount retail.

author: @angelcovarrubias3418
comments: @@JosephCarlsonAfterHours Fair enough and good luck with it.

author: @realestalex2728
comments: AWS has 3 pricing schemes (pay for what you use on a granularity of up to milliseconds, bid for leftover resources at a steep discount or lease out resources with an upfront payment) that has 2 advantages, on one hand it provides flexibility for costumers when it comes to pay for AWS resources, secondly it allows for AWS to make the most of every available resource, every time they builds a new servers location they can be somewhat sure that they can put those resources up for a good use. Additionally AWS takes advantage of the basic concept of redundancy to take more income per user by still being significantly cheaper and more practical for users than on premise servers, the high cost of changing cloud infrastructure in addition to the contracts mentioned in the video makes up for a pretty good moat, not an unbreakable business model but still these are some of the ups I have rarely heard people talk about.

author: @mmansinh
comments:
Stock splits to make stock in $100-200 range are good. Especially good for regular retail investors who want to be able to do option trades on the stock. A simple example would be to buy the stock and sell calls when you think it has gone too high or hedge earnings etc. 

If the stock is $3000, you would need a portfolio of $2-$4 million if you did not want AMZN to be too big a portion of your portfolio. However, if it were $150, you could buy 100-200 shares of AMZN and be able to sell calls on it easily. 

The other part where smaller $50-$150 priced stocks are better is the narrower bid/ask in option trades - just look at the wide spreads for options for these 4-digit stocks. The market makers and those who pay for order flow can game the system and give you poor execution ....

author: @najhussain9498
comments: Hi David... the growth rates you have used... over how many years ? As it stands at 500 billion so if you did 5 years thats 1.5 trillion and the highest atm is about 600 billion in the world for a company... so how does a company go to 1.5 trillion or so in 5 years or so? Interested to hear your views... thanks

author: @StockScreenApp
comments: Hi Naj - not sure I understand the context of your question? The growth I used was over 5 years.

author: @najhussain9498
comments: @@StockScreenApp Hi David - Amazons current revenue is 500b - so at 25% growth per year it would be 1.5 T in 5 years... is that correct ? If so isn't that unrealistic considering the largest companies in the world including Amazon trade around with a revenue of 500 to 600 billion per year ? - The point I am making is that is the revenue growth used for big companies not likely to occur at them figures? Thanks

author: @StockScreenApp
comments: @@najhussain9498 my growth rates are based on earnings and as you know - earnings are heavily suppressed with Amazon. Cloud and 3P are high margin sectors but 3P is being used to make up for their normal retail and loss-making prime divisions. You can sit with these numbers for months but at the end of the day, it's still a guessing game. While I do make these DCF models to get a general idea - I don't invest based on it. I base my overall thesis on it is -  is the company growing, will they continue to grow, is it high quality and am I overpaying right now. I hope this makes sense.

author: @najhussain9498
comments: @@StockScreenApp Hey David - Yes absolutely - Sorry I wasn't criticising, I was just trying to get my head around it as many people say the same thing or predict the growth of companies naturally at those levels but then the final figure just seems too unrealistic in 5 or 10 years. However, on a final note, when you say earnings growth, do you like to refer to the sales revenue or the net profit ? As ultimately we all want to establish the current value of the company so that we can determine if it is likely to grow stock wise in the future? Thanks again :-) Your channel is brilliant and I really value your thoughts.

author: @StockScreenApp
comments: @@najhussain9498 no didn't take it as criticism at all. They are really good questions and happy to answer them for you. With earnings, I mean the net income. However with Amazon they generally get valued based on their operating cash flow. If you look at the share price vs the operating cash flow you will see that it follows the same trajectory. But usually I look at the earnings and the free cash flow. You will find that stocks generally follow the earnings. However with some stocks you might find that FCF is a better way to value them. In terms of growth stocks you generally look at the price to sales again.

1) Now average folks can sell covered calls against their position and generate some income. Say you're conservative and generate 2% from those call premiums annually and you reinvest the proceeds back into Amazon, overtime that compounds quickly

author: @zacharysullivan4522

After watching many of your videos, I've come to the conclusion that the way you value companies results in missing out on almost all the great companies of the past 20 years. Great companies demand higher valuations. By your metrics, Amazon was historically never a buy. In retrospect that's obviously not a great financial decision.

Have you considered that 'growth' investing has outperformed 'value' investing for decades now? And not by a small margin either. I'm struggling to see what you see out there as a good deal. All you've been recommending are companies like Alibaba and Intel, which despite being such 'deals' have only sunk further and further.

author: @saeedTHEgreat
comments:
I agree with you. They try to sell a software that doesn't pass the backtest. Their method works for finding safe and well-stablished large companies which trade at a decent price, but they will miss on so many growth stories. Company like Amazon has monopoly, technological advancement, and pricing power that should be considered.
Other than growth companies, they would also miss on Asset plays, as they ignore the book values in their eight pillars. They would also miss on turn-around companies whose numbers are basically trash, but are at at inflection point to change their business. They probably even miss on cyclicals. 
They should also consider that the average P/E of S&P correlates with the interest rate. If the 30-yr bond has 4% rate, the P/E could go as high as 25.
There are so many factors in evaluating a good company that makes it hard to create a one-fits-all method.

author: @TbirdThunderstruck
comments:
Counter arguments to why I think Amazon is undervalued:
1) it's price to sales (2.5) is lowest it's been in 7 years ago, cheapest FAANGM stock by this metric. 
2) Operating cash flow average of the last 2 years is 5% of market cap, consistently having while consistently growing revenue by 20% per year. 
3) Amazon likely has a stronger moat than most of the big tech companies now with combining Ecommerce and logistics. Extremely capital intensive to do what Amazon has been doing the past few years.
4) Alphabet and Meta likely a much larger decline in earnings if we have a recession. Marketing budgets are the first to get slashed in downturns. People switch between social media platforms too, every decade or 2. A wider moat allows chance to fatten margins and survive longer.

author: @mkbbk7722
comments: 3:22: a flaw in your analysis about the ad business is, that the overall market place is shrinking. Sellers compete at super low margins and now Amazon is fueling this even more with ads. For the short term this means massive, high margin growth. In the mid- run it has already become apparent that many sellers are leaving amazon because it is becoming increasingly difficult for to make sufficient margins. Conservatively estimating, if average margins for sellers fell by only 5%, 40% of them would leave the market place, not spending on ads, nor generating FBA commission. The market place is consolidating where niches will be dominated by certain players, who in return generate little ad income for amazon and have relatively better negotiating power due to size.

author: @christiansantos3216
comments: I came to a similar conclusion, but assumed significant growth in margins for a variety of reasons. Amazon delivery vans are currently Benz Diesel vans with 14.5 mpg and I have read online that mpg is much worse for delivery drivers since they stop so often. Based off the 10B deliveries in the past 5 years since amazon began it‚Äôs own delivery business  (with 4B just from last year), I also assume every delivery is a conservative one mile. Then took the average diesel price over the past years (~2.49).The Rivian fleet of 100,000 that amazon ordered is slowly replacing the fleet and has already been seen in the streets. The average cost of charging a rivian van is $10.80, however that‚Äôs for consumers and amazon is the largest consumer of green energy in the US. By the end of 2020 they already had 64 wind turbines and covered numerous factories in solar panels and were generating 6.8GW. They are 5 years ahead of schedule in their plans to become carbon neutral. Amazon plans to charge their fleet with their own energy, use their own energy for AWS which is super energy intensive then sell the rest.

author: @christiansantos3216
comments: Even assuming amazon will only deliver 10B packages again in the next 5 years (which is super conservative bc it assumes no growth despite the growth from 0-10B in 5 years), and they will have to pay consumer prices for electricity the switch to EV will save Amazon some 25B in the next 5 years. This does not even include the synergies in costs it‚Äôs huge investments in green energy implies for lowering the margins across their businesses. It‚Äôs the equivalent of every arm of amazon that runs on AWS no longer having to pay for any energy which will allow them to push down margins and price competition out.

author: @christiansantos3216
comments: The company has yet to explore buy backs, dividends, raising prime pricing, stock splits

author: @christiansantos3216
comments: Ad business will grow much faster with Apple cracking down on App Store tracking, which amazon is not subject to because of Alexa‚Ä¶which is going to be the first voice assistant to travel to space.

author: @trent1615
comments: Why would anyone put money into Amazon over Tesla? Look Amazon is a perfectly good investment they have an excellent e-commerce business, cloud computing (that‚Äôs where the majority of revenue comes from) and still some upside and now an excellent advertising component. Here‚Äôs the problem lots of competition in these areas with some big dogs like Facebook, Microsoft,google and apple. Amazons best growth days are behind and will grow well but likely in the mid teens. Tesla has a better balance sheet similar Forward PE a much better PEG. Will likely grow at a 50% plus at least for the next five years. They are also competing against legacy automotive companies which when compared to great companies like google, Facebook, apple and Microsoft they are a joke and half a decade behind Tesla and many will likely go bankrupt failing to transition from ICE to EV. Beyond just the opportunity Tesla has with EV they are also disrupting energy sector which has the largest TAM, insurance, FSD licensing, robo Taxi and more. So while Amazon is a perfectly fine company I just can‚Äôt justify putting capital into them when Tesla is trading at a similar forward PE but has a much longer runway for growth. Global EV sales being about 7% that within the next 10-15 years will be 100%. The Robo Taxi opportunity alone is almost impossible to evaluate it would be like trying to value the TAM of the internet back in the early 90s we just know the opportunity is likely in the Trillions and Tesla is in the lead widening the gap every day. So when you sit back and compare Amazons optionality to Tesla they are not even in the same league. Just look at the fundamentals profit margins, operating margins, return on assets and return on equity Tesla is better in every category. Also like I already pointed out who would you rather compete with google, fb, apple and Microsoft or competing against trash legacy automotive companies like GM and Ford? On top of that Tesla is lead by Elon like him or not he maybe the greatest CEO of this generation. If someone can tell me how Amazon is a better investment than Tesla I would love to hear.

author: @dylansneed4974
comments:
I first want to say thank you for the countless hours of work that you've put into this channel. I feel like my family and I have benefitted greatly from the information you've shared here. I've got great respect for you, and that's why I'm asking this question. What do you think of Amazon's corporate ethics? 

I myself have tried to research this, and from what I've found, I disagree with many of their business practices: harsh working conditions, predatory marketing/manufacturing, and just the overall monopolistic nature of their business. Are they innovative? Sure! Have they produced great returns for their shareholders? Absolutely! But at what cost to the world? I think you can argue that they have hurt mom & pop businesses, they take advantage of the people that sell on their platform, and they do not treat at least some of their warehouse employees with respect.

It's for these and other reasons that I am not buying AMZN stock buy itself. I'm invested in VTI and VOO, so I've made a judgment call there, but that's where I've drawn the line for me. I genuinely would love to hear your thoughts on this topic, and I think a lot of other people would, too.

You guys are amazing, and I'm going to keep watching your videos. Just wanted to bring up something that's important to me. Thank you again for everything!

author: @gratkov
comments: @dylan please explain how amazon is a monopoly, thanks!

author: @h.h.amford702
comments:
As an ex-employee of Amazon I can tell you: I never worked in a company with better work conditions.

That said, I didn't work for Amazon in the States, but in Europe.

author: @dylansneed4974
comments:
@@gratkov I tried to word my comment carefully. I think their business model is monopolistic in nature. Are they technically a monopoly? I'm not sure. But they are "the everything store". They consistently copy designs by their own seller and undercut them in price. I suppose that could be construed as shrewd business practice, but it just seems kinda crappy and disingenuous to me. And about 1/3 of the worldwide cloud computing infrastructure is on AWS. I guess it just wigs me out a bit thinking of one company with so many fingers in so many pies.

I don't know if that answers your question. I'm not an expert. Just a normal dude trying his best to research and make not only wise investments, but actually support companies whose mission I believe in. Might be a little pie-in-the-sky, but I do think there are some companies out there who are doing more good than harm--and unfortunately the opposite is probably true as well. All the best!

author: @dylansneed4974
comments: @@h.h.amford702 I'm glad your experience was good! I would love to hear from warehouse workers in America specifically. Maybe I've only heard anecdotes and hearsay, but it seemed like I was hearing it quite a lot.

author: @brandont5408
comments:
Mimi stock splits and reverse splits are simple enough. I will give two scenarios that hopefully help give clarity on what these terms mean.

Scenario 1.) A Stock Split. In 2020 Tesla decided to split their stock at a 5:1 ratio. Meaning shareholders went from owning one stock to five stocks. Tesla did this because the value per share was $2,213.40 and they wanted to reduce the cost per share so they could attract a broader range of investors who would buy at the lower price. So if you owned this stock you would have went from owning one stock at $2,213.40 to five shares valued at $442.68 which collectively would have been worth the same amount as before the split. Over time these individual shares climbed in value from $442.68 to a peak of $1,144.76 before dropping with the rest of the market in recent months.

Scenario 2.) Reverse Split. Basically the exact opposite of a split where a company combines shares to boost the price per share. This can be done for many reasons, but is often done to get stocks values above $5.00 as anything below is often considered penny stocks, and can face some trading restrictions by brokerages. So in this scenario a stock worth $1.00 in a 1:10 reverse split would become worth $10.00, but instead of having ten shares you would now have only one.

Hopefully that clarifies the terminology for you. If you have any further questions I am sure others here will be glad to help.

author: @leakyabstraction
comments: Intel is in an abysmal situation currently, because they grew complacent due to the earlier lack of competition, and have lost the innovation race to AMD, not to mention that Apple also switched to in-house CPUs. But I think there are reasons to believe that Intel is close to their bottom now, and they have a track record of coming back as market leaders; this is not the first time they lost it. 12th gen Intel CPUs already outperformed the currently available AMD CPUs, to a degree that most tech channels explicitly started to recommend Intel again over AMD. But this coincided with the supply chain issues and the beginning of the economic turmoil, so they couldn't really capitalize on it. I'm not saying Intel is a good short-term investment, but I think over the longer term it can easily provide a very significant return.

author: @sdtok527
comments:
I think it is not about the numbers but about the story. Facebooks story has changed. 

Once it was the ONLY relevant social media, but although their userbase growed, competition has been more and more fierce lately. The moat and peoples attention is under pressure.
Once it had the best analytic data, it knew what you did, and could target you. But now ads are everywhere: podcasts, (other) social media, streaming platforms are adopting it, amazon has it (closest ad to buy button). And Apple kicked their data sharing between apps.

I do not see their user base growing much more (~25% world population). I dont see the price of ads going up. I dont see their expenses going down (they actually have gone up a lot!). 

So you are betting on a VR play, not on the current social media anymore. Because their current business model is under attack.

Your free cash flow (and revenue) growth assumption seems way too low. Even if you're bearish on the stock. As you said, they invest most of their free cash flow in growth capex. If Amazon really wanted to they could 3x their free cash flow next year by cutting back on all their investing.

author: @Carlos.Damiao
comments:
I like when Paul shows his conservative assumptions, and then changes them to make a point. But again, Paul you can NOT change the revenue without changing the PE. If Amazon makes 22% revenue growth on average for 10 years, there is absolutely no way they will be selling with 18 PE.
Of course they won't be selling for 100 PE. But at the very least 25.
We can't assume (for simulation purposes, not that we actually believe it will happen) a 22% revenue growth and use at the same time the argument "I'm going with a PE of 18 because they are big so they will have a harder time growing". 22% revenue growth for a company with the size of Amazon is huge, and should be treated as such.
TL;DR: When we adjust the revenue we have to think if it affects the PE we are assuming.

author: @estring123
comments: isn't the 18 p/e the terminal value? very fair for such a large company

author: @Carlos.Damiao
comments:
‚Äã@@estring123 P/E is the price to earnings ratio.
It doesn't really matter how big the company is. It only matters how fast it is growing. It's easier for a smaller company to grow faster then a bigger company, but here we are already assuming an annualized 22% revenue growth. Which is quite big for a 10 year period.
But my point isn't even about Amazon.
Paul in the beginning assumed a growth of 14% and with a P/E of 18. Then changed the revenue growth to 22%, but didn't adjust the P/E.
Should a company sell for the same P/E when compared between 14% revenue growth and 22% revenue growth? I think the answer is obviously no.

author: @estring123

author: @Hylin79
comments: Fundamental analysis is a good screener to find stable growth or mature companies at a discount, but just doesn't work as well on fast growth companies or companies facing major disruptions that have yet to show up on financials. Amazon could've easily missed their chance with cloud just like Nokia and Blackberry missed out on touchscreen smartphones, but they bet big, same as Microsoft, and that's how they became FAANG. Neither of their core businesses (Amazon in e-commerce, Microsoft in operating system) generated the kind of explosive growth post dot-com bubble that could justify high p/e's. In the 27 years that Amazon has existed, I think there were little to none buy opportunities if you had relied on fundamental analysis alone for Amazon.

comments: Great video. Regarding anti-trust concerns: Worst case scenario, Amazon gets broken up (1% chance???). As an investor in AMZN I say, "Please, do me that favor!" Amazon Web Services, alone, has trailing revenues of $53B and is growing at mid-30%. If it were a stand-alone company, it would easily fetch 25X sales, giving it a value of about $1.3T. "Highway robbery" doesn't seem to adequately describe this valuation. I'm already loaded up with as much AMZN as I can carry, but if I wasn't, I'd be buying more.

‚Äã@@VTmyET69420LaTesla i am an accountant. i can understand why people take out depreciation expense. company already spent that money, it will have no impact on future cash outflow. in theory it's just on paper. 

when u value a balance sheet in stock, do u look at how much their building / machine is worth? the fact that patent are sometimes not value on balance sheet, can grossly understate a company balance sheet. people care about cashflow because it's the common ground on what everyone speak. if u can bring positive cash flow in the future. people buy. 

EBIDTA sometimes is just a paper amount. amortization assumption (years assumption) sometimes doesn't reflect reality.

author: @manyinwong
comments:
as an accountant myself. i never made that sound in the public. 

- i also understand that accounting standards can be inflexible, time consuming, and sometimes doesn't reflect the reality, but it provides grounds to compare between companies (but it still varies) 

- time value of money is a tool, but discount rate is subjective. everyone has their way to value a stock. stock price is the average of everyone expectation, if u are too hawkish, u can never buy a stock. (because ur buy in price is too low), the fact that u report contract income and discount it back also reflect how accounting standards itself can be base on assumption. 

- for example - average people don't even look at depreciation / amortization, they care about cash flow. The company already spent that money. (useful life is so subjective, most of the time building.) - people only look at cash flow is because of the assumption that cash is what keep the company afloat, and for tech, it would mean more R&D. the fact that if u don't have cash flow. the company will sink. 

Accountants cannot be pigeon hole in accounting principles. people like amazon because of their multi business stream. they evolve. they are entering new business, new market, finding new ways to make revenue. looking PE is flat out retarded. u will never find amazon at 20 PE (u will never get an opportunity to buy amazon at 20FPE / PE ) - average tech company. just because amazon premium is base on their multi stream business.

I totally disagree with your viewpoint. 

For one, Amazon's capex is gigantic and thus is hard to fathom. Last year, they spent double the entire value of Walmart' existing infrastructure, and that project was just in the US. They also spend more on R&D than the other FAANG stocks combined. 

Going further, I'd say Amazon is the very definition of a spawner. In the last quarter, they announced they are going to lisence the tech behind their checkout-less stores that are estimated to decrease the expenses of running a brick and mortar store by up to 70%. This naturally provides a collosal market. Amazon's retail side also looks to be flourishing a brighter future with the Buy with Prime function allowing Amazon utilise their logistics service for items sold through third parties. A cool factoid is Amazon earn more in advertising than YouTube

I own Baba as my number 1 holding, but aim at rapidly investing in Amazon

author: @jonp3674
comments:
Great quality as always. I think it's really cool how much you're putting into the channel to help it grow, I think youtube channels grow exponentially so the first bit can be a real slog but it's inspiring to see you just calmly putting in the hours to make the vids. And yeah I really like them so I appreciate it.

I really think re amazon the etailer half of the business is close to worthless. The narrative was always that they would lose money while scaling and then at scale they could increase margins and rake in loads of cash, but the truth is competition is so fierce that they won't ever be able to raise prices imo. Shopify, ebay, pinterest, other people's web stores etc, there's really no moat in etail.

I think honestly AWS is the only really good bit of the business, I think it's kind of worth modelling the two parts separately just because they're so different in terms of margins and capital requirements.

So yeah I'm probably rather more negative on it than you are.

author: @HEJInvesting
comments:
Thank you man, really appreciate that. I'll continue investing in the idea of this channel and the production of the videos as it grows and I prove to myself that I can generate a growing audience. It definitely is a slog, and I'm glad you mentioned the hours because on the surface the assumption from most people (and it's understandable) is that people making videos don't spend much time doing it, when in reality, a lot goes into them. With that being said, getting to talk about something I'm genuinely interested in and then hear other perspectives and counter arguments is great and makes the challenge a lot easier! 

I get your point regarding the ecommerce segment, it's a fair argument considering the current margins. My perspective is that people will be happy to pay premiums (whether that be in the price of the products themselves, or indirectly through a subscription like Prime) for the convenience (i.e. same day/next day delivery and also a shop that sells literally anything/everything) that Amazon offers which should help to drive margins. Competition is definitely fierce but I think with them being an early dominator in this space, it has generated them the capital to be able to lay all of the infrastructure down (i.e. huge fulfilment centres in most built-up areas) which means other businesses can't compete in terms of their offering and efficiency. 

Valuing the businesses separately definitely makes a lot of sense though, we can agree on that haha! As a "back of the envelope valuation" I think AWS could easily command a 10x P/S ratio in the current market based on sector, growth and margins, so approximately $600bn for that business. What do you think?

author: @jonp3674
comments:
@@HEJInvesting Yeah I can understand the editing and research must take a long time, you get nice quality out of it though :)

Yeah I think that's a fair valuation for AWS, I mean 38% growth in a year is really impressive. I also think that as time goes on more and more businesses will move into the cloud and start using AI which means there is a lot of room to grow here, giant future market potential. 

I've also heard it's quite hard to switch clouds, as you need to move all your data and pipelines and retain all your staff. So yeah that's quite important, once people are in they're probably pretty sticky.

I do see your point that having a giant fulfilment network already built out is really valuable. It may also have some synergies, like businesses that start out selling on Amazon might naturally move into AWS as they grow.

comments: Hey, I‚Äôm a fellow Chicagoland guy and dividend investor, and I‚Äôm curious about your thoughts on a non-dividend stock.  Undoubtedly, you have been in Portillos and are aware of their stock (PTLO).  It doesn‚Äôt pay a dividend, but I am curious what you would see as it‚Äôs faults outside of not paying dividends.  I imagine you‚Äôre personally familiar with how busy all of their restaurants are all the time.  I bought a few shares simply because it‚Äôs way down off its IPO, owned by Berkshire Hathaway, and expanding.  I would appreciate any thoughts you have on their future.

author: @DapperDividends
comments:
Hey fellow Chicagoland guy! So yeah, I‚Äôm very familiar with Portillos, and from quickly looking at the company, to me it doesn‚Äôt look terrible‚Ä¶..shares outstanding are decreasing and are at 32 million, sales have been ticking up, but they have negative return on equity, a bit of debt and a low interest coverage ratio.

Honestly, with them being a small cap stock, they have lots of room for growth, id like to see the debt being paid down because with rates rising it‚Äôs going start becoming more expensive‚Ä¶

Not paying a dividend is perfectly fine because they are a company trying to grow, so a dividend wouldn‚Äôt make sense right now.

I have had my eye on them, and I would honestly go to their investor relations page and read their annual report and CEO statement to get a feel of where they are and where they plan on going.

I had forgot about Portillos stock and I may just grab 4-5 shares to hold and forget about, but I wouldn‚Äôt put a large amount on them just in case things go sideways.

But, I think they‚Äôll be around and I remember hearing they want to expand into other markets‚Ä¶.

Hope my thoughts help a bit!ü´°

author: @perwis9893
comments: Important point on heuristics. Lots of investors are lazy, for example relying on what other people think (‚Äùpolling your peers‚Äù) and making judgements on easy to calculate financial ratios. This creates opportunites for investors who are willing to do the work, and able to think for themselves.

author: @investingiq
comments: Thanks mate! I thought you might find it interesting. The heuristic section really opened my eyes to how the mind looks for shortcuts and one has to be really disciplined to ignore it. And you're right, it creates opportunities for investors like us looking deeper than others! Analyzing 08 Amazon was actually really beneficial for me. Before I knew their figures, I kind of assumed back in the early days, they had really low returns on capital as they were scaling (especially free cash flow returns on capital). I expected it to be ok but not as good as it was. I cant believe people were ignoring a business with 30% free cash flow ROCE and 100% reinvestment rate with 20B Market Cap... its absolutely crazy to me lol

author: @perwis9893
comments: Great analysis! I think a really great investment has a good baseline return, with predictable cash flows, but also lots of optionality. I think this is what Amazon was in 2008. The optionality resulted especially in AWS, which was very hard to predict in 2008. But even without AWS Amazon would probably not been a bad investment, which was what Nick Sleep saw early on.

author: @investingiq
comments: Yeah I agree. AWS has been one hell of a homerun business though haha. The only company I can think of with sort of the same characteristics is maybe Tesla, in terms of runway and optionality. Its just waaay bigger than Amazon (market cap) was back in the day. Not sure Tesla can 100x from here...

author: @oldscratch3535
comments:
I work at Daniel Defense. There's been a huge crackdown on counterfeit DD items lately. We have flyers at work showing all of the items that have been copied and how to tell the difference. There are some fake rails out there that are actually pretty hard to spot. The way we tell is by specific marks made during steps of the manufacturing process that are unique to our jigs and how we make stuff. The laser engraving font, quality, and placement is also a good way to tell real from fake.

The plastic itself on the copy is probably not all that bad. Its the fitment, springs, pins, finishing, etc that is usually shit tier. I'm not 100% sure, but I think Magpul makes all of the polymer stuff for us. I don't mess with finished parts much. There are plans to bring it in house at some point.

author: @Myopinion23
comments: On the cash flow statement, they add back change in NOWC to get the Cash flows from operations. Why do you subtract the change in NOWC in order to get Free cash flow? I feel like if you calculated out the change in NOWC using the balance sheet then you would need to subtract it, but when using the cash flow statement it is accounted for based on its effects on cash. I.e. Inventory growth would be positive if you calculated change in NOWC using the balance sheet and would be negative if you calculated NOWC using the numbers on the statement of cash flows

author: @christiansteele9296
comments: Think about it like this, the additional inventory added onto the balance sheet is a use of cash. You are using cash to buy inventory which means you need to subtract out that cash outflow to be properly reflected in the FCF calculation.

author: @Shounen_Mania

‚Äã@@Value-Investing Sure, about the first part of your statment, but I think people are using Munger's endorsement of BABA to support to bullishness a little too loosely sometimes. BABA's total value in the Daily Journal's portfolio is less than $100M, while Berkshire holds at least $1B.

20x for the normal scenario when assessing its core retailer business seems fair, even without growth (or smth close to 5-8%). But, Sven, AWS is probably the best future business that will exist. High costs of change, extreme recurring revenue with almost no churn. Possibility to increase the price since customers have grown their ecosystem in the AWS platform. author: @Amwatson801
comments:
@@brandonjones3187 They are value investors: they buy fundamentally solid companies at a discount. Very hard to lose money doing that.
You have to ask yourself what kind of growth is necessary in order to justify the price tag of a company.
Amazon reached a high of 188 in 2021. If I expect a 10% return per year, assume their free cashflow margins remain at 2020 levels and assume a terminal P/FCF multiple of 20, I need them to grow their revenue 25% per year over the next 5 years (and then half that in years 6-10) in order to justify that 188 price tag.
Amazon's revenue was 470b last year: if you grow that 25% per year for 5 years you get 1.5T. Stop to think for a moment: the GDP of France is 2.6T. Do you think that makes sense? I guess it is certainly possible, but are you willing to bet on that, risking a substantial portion of your net worth?
A value investor essentially makes no bets: he chooses businesses that are straightforward to understand, and are thus easy to value, and buys them at a discount.
That is what Buffet, Lynch or Pabrai do.
I think we can all agree that their process does work. It is a matter of having a solid screening process, monitoring a watchlist of companies that you understand well, and going in big when opportunities materialize (which is generally the moment of maximum market pessimism). Sort of what happened with Alibaba or what is about to happen with Intel.

So, I think INTC new CEO is following the same footstep but a slight different approach. Looking at KPMG semiconductor metrics, we all know that there is a shortage in chip supplies and ASML is trying to keep up the demand. INTC has other competitors (TSMC & Samsung) that are competing to build fabs in the US to try and keep up with the demand. author: @WealthGambit
comments: Great question there is actually a very large moat or coffin. Legacy banks have a significant amount of physical locations and staff to run/manage those locations, that cost a lot of Money. What was once an asset is now a liability, if there's anything we learned in 2020 it's that physical locations have their setbacks. Fintechs like Sofi are unburdened by infrastructure that legacy banks have spent decades maybe even centuries building (maybe their coffins), because of this they can pass those savings on the consumer and produce even more competitive rates (once bank charter is approved)! We actually made a whole video on it here! SOFI STOCK: Why BANKS Can't COMPETE! Watch Before It's TOO LATE! -  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zGdNDuOU0Z0&t=296s

author: @sanjeevgig8918
comments: @@WealthGambit You don't understand the concept/definition of a moat. CoFi / BoFi / ChaseFi could start tomorrow.

author: @WealthGambit
comments:
@@sanjeevgig8918 Watch the video first then get back to us. Everyone said "omg legacy automakers will crush TESLA they'll just start making electric vehicles and then Tesla will disappear" and yet Tesla stands hear with over a TRILLION dollar market cap surpassing the top 5 automakers. Why didn't the legacy automakers just crush Tesla? Because they had sunk so much money into developing the ICE (Internal Combustion Engine) vehicles which are inferior to electric aka they were encumbered. On top of that their distribution method ended up hurting them  and trying untangled themselves from that distribution route would have bankrupted some of them. Tesla had a significant technological advantage & started first & also they were unencumbered by the outdated infrastructure. The same thing is happening with Sofi, banks are tangled up in all these physical branches which before technology were necessary but now are a burden. You want a clear competitive advantage against legacy banks 1. unencumbered by expensive outdated infrastructure 2. technology 3. management 4. one of the highest if not the highest lifetime value of a customer 5

I could go on and on but luckily we have entire playlist dedicated to this feel free to check them out lol.

author: @markhall7222
comments: What the SEC filing does not say is that each share bought or sold until the close on June 3 carries the rights to the 20-1 split. Split rights are, in effect, transferred from the seller to the buyer when you purchase the stock. The seller loses the right; the buyer gains the right. Since Amazon will not issue additional stock between May 27 and June 3 ALL outstanding AMZN shares have inherent split rights. ALL shares purchased next week will have 20-1 split rights.

comments: Horrible for investors.  I respectfully disagree that R/S is good.  Usually it ends up with a huge, huge loss.  Better hope it just goes beyond 10.00 to avoid a split.

comments: Yeah, the point was that a R/S is not necessarily bad. It however does not mean it is good.

author: @Steve-dv9kd
comments: @@ytfinance 100% R/S is a huge loss for investors.  Good luck to anyone who holds through a split.  Let‚Äôs hope the price goes up without, or disaster will occur.

author: @ytfinance
comments: Explain how it is bad from an equity standpoint? If I own $1000 worth of 50 shares and then a reverse split takes place of 5 for 1 I would simply have $1000 worth of 10 shares. Only the number of shares  decrease. Clearly investors will likely freak out and sell the stock without thinking but the split itself will do not harm, however investors selling because they think a split is bad will negatively impact the stock. What are your thoughts?

author: @Steve-dv9kd
comments: @@ytfinance Most people who have knowledge can tell you that your 5 for one split will be right back to the starting price within 1-2 years.  Example 100 shares for 7.00 splits 5-1.  20 shares at 35.00.  In a year or two the price will most likely be under 20.00 and in two years 7-10.00.  Look up past companies R:S.  FTR is a good one to learn from.

author: @ytfinance
comments: The point is proven, from an equity standpoint the reverse split does nothing. It is only investors negative association of the split that makes it negative. According to analysts and other professionals Sofi stock has higher price targets than what the stock is currently trading at which means that in the next 2 years the stock price could be higher than it is today, especially because the company will be profitable by then. Now I do not think it would be beneficial for the company to do a RSS because of how investors will take it, but none the less it would not matter much over the long run.

author: @Steve-dv9kd
comments: R/S usually go back to where it started.  Definitely will sell.

author: @nolas1360
comments: @@Steve-dv9kd Agree, if this becomes reality, I'm selling out too.

author: @nolas1360
comments: The reverse stock split is being voted on for POSSIBLE future use.  If we don't go into a major recession, they'll never have to use it.  You'll probably see a lot of companies doing reverse splits if we go into a bad recession.  They listed a few other possible ways of dealing with it, but everyone seems to want to jump on the reverse stock split for views.  I don't like the stock based compensations, but it's pretty much standard for high growth companies.  Student loan fud is old news, and they've been beating without it.  The reverse stock split, as of now, is not happening and will be voted on in July and used only for an emergency if that's the path they choose to go down.  The title is misleading and should be Possible reverse stock split.

author: @ytfinance
comments: I agree with the stock analysis. Also, the title is meant to signify the topics that I will talk about in the video and the reverse stock split is one such topic.

author: @mkbbk7722
comments:
As an FBA Seller for 3 years I would like to offer my bearish perspective. 
- Overall marketplace GMV is dropping 
- Competition between sellers is fierce, meaning that seller margins are compressing, this is why amazon is still growing mainly due to ADS, yet this isnt sustainable.
- For myself an average seller on the side with low six figure turnover, even a 5-10% loss in margin would make the whole FBA business unprofitable, meaning that for a lot of sellers there is a breaking line where they will leave the platform, which in return will loose in attractiveness due to lower variability and after consolidation higher prices. 
- AWS: Quick point to AWS, as a lot of talking points are about how it will carry amazon stock to new heights, competition is really coming PLUS: AWS customer base has a systematic risk with the number of customers that are unprofitable, for instance VC backed startups, of which a high amount will fail. 
- Europe and the US have more socialist regimes now, tax optimization will not work as well anymore
- Higher marginal cost per package delivered, due to higher minimum wage and higher gas prices, the EV infrastructure will take at least 10 more years to be able to replace fossil and will require substantial investment from amazon TODAY.
- Geopolitical tensions: Where do you think all the junk on amazon is from? Yes, its china, whether you buy a cycling pump or a new phone charger, its 90% from china. Tariffs, etc. could sweep those products of the marketplace soon PLUS most of it is garbage and people are becoming much more sensitized toward buying less and buying less junk.
- Global supply chain issues: in short: For packages from China I have paid 4x to 2 years ago lately. All this is eating into margins, margins matter as previously said to keep depth of inventory etc. high. 

in Summary: IMO Amazon will half within 24 months.

author: @jko1501
comments:
You should expect this to drastically increase their profits because they pay us heavily in stock instead of cash. This will reduce their overhead. They used to only pay significant portions of wages to AWS white collar workers with stock,  but now that its nominal price is lower and they can offer it to lower paid employees like those in the warehouse their profits will blow up. Total share value offered as an annual raise or sign on bonus have to be within a certain percentage of current wage/ salary range. If the share price is too high then many low paid employees get priced out. 
(...And with almost a million warehouse workers world wide...)

In reference to the cap ex, you should note that AWS spends between $5-7Billion per new data center and they're expanding very fast. Check VA as a reference.
